 so successful and highly rated  RESOURCES  Due to many files which had formats incompatible to our server for storage  we have provided a dropbox location from where workshop resources may be downloaded  You will need a dropbox account profile to use this cloud storage site  Please email  roycm vmi edu if you have problems  2015 STEM Education Conference Dropbox   Workshop Resources   2015 STEM Workshops 3D Printing in a Middle School Makerspace   Grades 5 8  Administrators 3D printing  Moving students from Replicator to Creator  lecture presentation 3D printers are absolutely mesmerizing  They light up and make wonderful sounds  Students of all ages are drawn to the idea of a 3D printers  They want to try it out but they have no idea how to do it  During this session we will walk you through the hurdles we encountered once we added a 3D printer into our Makerspace  We will share with you how we are slowly moving our students from just printing what someone else made to creating their own original creations to print  We will even show you how to digitize yourself to 3D print  This workshop covers technology for teachers and administrators with students in grades 5 8  Instructors   Susan Jinks  Ph  D  Instructional Technology Specialist  Falls Church City Public School  Dr  Susan Jinks is an instructional technology specialist at Mary Ellen Henderson Middle School  MEH  in Falls Church City  VA  Jinks helped her school deploy a 1 1 laptop program during the 2014 school year  In addition  she successfully co wrote a grant to establish a Makerspace in the school library  She recently became a Google Educator and Google for Education Certified Trainer  Her doctoral work focused on the factors that lead to the perception of learning within a graduate online course   Lori Fogle  Librarian Media Specialist  Falls Church City Public School Add a New Dimension to Your Students  Learning  3D Printing in the Elementary Classroom   Grades 3 5 Attendees will experience a variety of web based software applications that students can use to integrate 3D printing into their learning  Come see how 3D printing can augment instruction and bring learning to life no matter what grade level or content area you teach  We will discuss how to incorporate 3D printing across subjects  troubleshoot common 3D printing issues  and provide practical advice on how to get students independent and productive with 3D printing  Creative ways to fund 3D printers and filament will also be explored  This workshop covers Technology for teachers with students in grades 3 5  Instructor   Karen Heathcock  Gifted Resource Teacher  Albemarle County Public Schools Karen is a Canadian who pursued teaching as a second career  She graduated from the Teacher s College at York University in Toronto  Ontario before moving to the United States in 2001  In addition to being endorsed in elementary education  she is also endorsed in economics  gifted education  and reading  Karen enjoys collaborating with classroom teachers to foster each student s ability to think critically  to problem solve  independently and collaboratively  to question at increasingly higher levels  and to create make with confidence and flexibility  These are the skills that make kids deeper thinkers  lifelong learners  and more productive  engaged citizens  Angling Your Neighborhood   Grades 6 8 For middle school mathematics teachers  finding a STEM application for angle relationships can be a struggle  During this workshop  attendees with participate in a lesson called  Angling Your Neighborhood  This lesson uses inquiry to discover different angle relationships  As attendees discover these relationships  they are challenged to use them to develop a neighborhood roadway system  By mixing inquiry with an engineering task  attendees are able to help their students develop the appropriate mathematics knowledge while applying that knowledge in a creative design and build activity  By participating in this hands on lesson  attendees will be prepared to take this ready made activity back to their middle school math classrooms  The activity is designed for the Virginia Math 8 Standards of Learning but can be adapted to the needs of sixth and seventh grade math by changing the criteria of the engineering task  Workshops covers integrated STEM for teachers with students in grades 6 8  Instructor   Kristine Vester  Educator  MathScience Innovation Center Kristine Vesteris a Mathematics Educator with the MathScience Innovation Center  MSiC  in Richmond  VA  In 2006  Kristine earned her M Ed  in Curriculum and Instruction  with a focus on mathematics  from VCU  Over a period of 11 years  Kristine has worked in several middle schools  focusing on mathematics and science education  In the Fall of 2008  Kristine joined the MSiC staff  Since then  she has been involved in creating innovative STEM lessons incorporating nanotechnology  engineering and fractals  for the virtual platform and the classroom  She has been a leader in different engineering programs for teachers  such as the VA STEM CoNNECT  as well as developing STEM Career programs for school counselors  Throughout her professional career  Kristine has been involved in developing and presenting professional developments on a local to national level  Her last two presentations were featured at the Regional NCTM Conference and the NSTA STEM Forum  Astronomical Tools   How to Use Them   Grades 3 8 Today there are a number of astronomical tools  telescopes  cameras  software  websites  available that an educator can use to enhance their student s learning experience  It can be a daunting task wading through all the options  and choosing the right one is not always easy  Once you have made your choice learning to use the tool can also be a time consuming task  where do you turn to for help  In this workshop we will give you an introduction to what s available in the way of tools and resources that are suitable for various education levels  From free to pricey we give you a rundown on what s out there  the  good  the bad  and the ugly  and where to get help  We will present the basics of how to choose and use binoculars  telescopes  cameras  and software as well as what to look for  and look out for  when it s time for you to make your choice  Weather permitting there will be an optional observing session in the evening   See the schedule for details  This workshop covers technology for educators and administrators with students in grades 3 8  Instructors     Lt  Col  Gregory Topasna  Ph  D  Department of Physics   Astronomy  Virginia Military Institute Dr  Topasna is a Professor of Physics at Virginia Military Institute in Lexington  VA  He is a graduate from VA Tech with a Ph D  in Physics and a concentration in astronomy  He has been teaching physics and astronomy since joining the VMI faculty in 2000 and conducts astronomical research on the polarization of starlight and the interstellar medium  Additionally  Dr  Topasna works with Dr  Daniela Topasna in the thin films laboratory at VMI where they fabricate and characterize thin film devices as well as Janus particles    Lt  Col  Daniela Topasna  Ph  D  Department of Physics   Astronomy  Virginia Military Institute Dr  Topasna is an associate professor in the department of physics and astronomy at Virginia Military Institute  Her research interests include fabrication and characterization of self assembled thin films  She has presented and authored several outreach activities in physics and nanotechnology    Blending Art  Language Arts and Linear Equations   Grades 5 8 Participants will all be given the same equations and blank paper to graph with NO guidance regarding scale factor  After equations are graphed  instructions will be to create a piece of art that uses color and texture to relate to some aspect of their life  As art is completed  comparisons of the  chevron  that emerges will be relevant to relating the art to the project based experience  A presentation will follow using students  work of the  Stained Glass  project  Sixth grade students began with a mini lesson in art appreciation  followed by graphing the same equations  VDOE  on larger paper  Periodic check ins using todaysmeet com were relevant to discuss various problems that students were having while navigating equations  Students gave feedback on each other s art  learning  through the project  slope and y intercept form and key elements to linear functions from a very elementary understanding  6th   8th grade curriculum  Students wrote a synopsis of what the artistic elements meant to them and how they chose to use materials and various elements to set the tone of the work of art  Students wrote a paper using google docs relating the art to the mathematics in a formal five paragraph format  Attendees will take away all handouts rubrics  etc  Numerous examples of student work will be used to explain the project and extend attendees view of what students can do when given the freedom to think critically and creatively  The session will culminate brainstorming ways that this project can be enhanced or ways students  work can be published  This workshop covers mathematics for teachers with students in grades 5 8  Instructor   Tabatha Myers  Teacher  Albemarle County Public Schools Tabatha has been teaching mathematics and science for ACPS for 12 years and has an B S  in Liberal Science  Elementary Ed  from Longwood University  In 2007  she received her Master of Education and Math Specialist Endorsement from the University of Virginia  She has taught sixth grade math her entire career  primarily located at the AVID demo school Jack Jouett Middle  She teaches a wide array of both math and science curriculum including all of middle school mathematics  Boat Design Challenge   Grades 6 8 A  Overview of 3 block lesson   lesson handouts included  B  Introduction to CAD software  1  pros cons of a few programs 2  Experiment with a few CAD tools  if computers for participants are available  3  See examples of student work and the sample that we will work with today C  Introduction to 3D printing            1  Types of printers with pros cons  prices  possible funding sources      2  Show how 3D printing supports concept understanding   Demo how changing one dimension affects volume     Print our sample design from the CAD file that participants have seen   See some previously printed examples of student work  D  Participants complete calculations on our sample design  E  Test calculations in tub of water This workshop covers SOL 6 10 d and 7 5 a c This workshop covers technology and math for teachers with students in grades 6 8  Instructors   Amy Effland  math science teacher and Adam Kuchta  CTE teacher  J T  Henley Middle School Amy Efflandteaches math science and Adam Kuchta teaches CTE at J T  Henley Middle School in Crozet  Virginia  Last school year they piloted this lesson in two 6th grade advanced math classes  The lesson was well received by students  parents and administration  They are excited to share this lesson with you today and look forward to hearing about its implementation in your classroom  Budgeting with M Ms   Grades 3 8 During this workshop participants will get to experience a hands on budget lesson that uses multiplication  addition  and subtraction  This lesson will introduce students to budgeting concepts like income and expenses  and the importance of using a budget  During the activity M Ms are used to represent income and expenses  Students are encouraged to have money left over at the end of the activity  Participants will receive a copy of the lesson plan and a sample package of the budgeting activity that can be reproduced over and over again  This lesson plan can be used for grades 4 and up  and covers Virginia SOLs 4 4b  5 4  and 6 3  This workshop covers mathematics for teachers with students in grades 3 8  Instructor   Sarah Landram  Community Financial Educator  DuPont Community Credit Union Sarah Landram is the Community Financial Educator at DuPont Community Credit Union  In her role as educator  she works with local schools  and other organizations to bring financial education lessons to much of the Central Shenandoah Valley  In 2012  she became a Certified Financial Counselor through the Credit Union National Association s FiCep program  She is a 2012 graduate of the Harrisonburg Rockingham Leadership program and a two time winner of the Desjardin Youth Financial Education Award for the state of Virginia  Sarah is also a certified trainer for the National Endowment for Financial Education  Prior to joining the Financial Education department  Sarah worked for 17 years in the Retail area at DCCU  CAREERS Project based Learning Program The Creative and Real World Engaging Experiences Realized this Summer  CAREERS  program was created for at risk and low performing 7th and 8th grade students as an alternative to a traditional summer school  Furthermore  research has shown that college and career readiness should be started in the middle school to help assess personal interest and future goals through career exploration  The program hired teachers to create project based learning units that were created around the 16 career clusters  Each project focused on competencies of problem solving  flexibility  collaboration and time management  It also embedded reading and math skills  The culminating project was for students to select one project and create a visual representation of the process of how they worked to create a project to answer a driving question or solve a challenge  In addition  students researched a potential career cluster of interest and presented it to community members  The hands on presentation will showcase the many projects that included some STEM PBL  MakerSpace  water rocket science  textile engineering  technologically related projects  t shirt shop  and the culminating project  Participants will examine the projects at different stations and fill out a handout that will prompt them to ask questions  write observations and how it could be used in other schools  After the activity  the presenters will answer questions  discuss the benefits and lessons learned from the program  The attendees will receive ideas and ways to incorporate project based learning units that include STEM and technology into their curriculum  The SOLSs covered will be non fiction reading skills  physical science SOLs and various math standards  This workshop covers project based learning for teachers and administrators with students in grades 7 8  Instructors      Rory Dippold  Ph  D CAREERS Coordinator   Civics   Economics Teacher  Falls Church City Schools Dr  Dippold is a Nationally Board Certified Teacher who has taught for twelve years in Falls Church City Schools  He is a Civics   Economics teacher who incorporates project based learning into his curriculum to create authentic learning experiences  In addition  his dissertation was titled   Infusing Self regulation Learning into Project based Learning  and he currently serves as an adjunct professor at George Mason University  He was recently honored as a Virginia Lottery  Super Teacher  award winner   Susan Jinks  Ph  D Technology Instructional Coach  Falls Church City Schools             Celebrating the International Year of Light 2015   Grades 3 8 This workshop includes hands on optics activities using readily obtainable materials  These activities are meant to explore and enhance knowledge about the nature and properties of light in a fun and educational way  Various teaching resources will be included  This workshop covers science for teachers with students in grades 3 8  Instructor   Lt  Col  Daniela Topasna  Ph  D  Department of Physics   Astronomy  Virginia Military Institute Dr  Topasna is an associate professor in the department of physics and astronomy at Virginia Military Institute  Her research interests include fabrication and characterization of self assembled thin films  She has presented and authored several outreach activities in physics and nanotechnology  The Chesapeake Challenge   Grades 5 8 Imagine being stranded in the woods with a nearby stream as your only source of water  Would you drink the water  There are many hidden pollutants in our natural water sources that can have a negative impact on your health  Luckily with the advancement in filtration methods  those pollutants can be removed to create safe drinking water  In this STEM challenge  participants will build their own filter and then test its efficiency at removing pollutants from the water  Based upon their results  participants will redesign to improve their filters  Connections will be made to the importance of the Chesapeake Bay ecosystem and the human impacts within its watershed  SOLs  6 5  6 7   This workshop covers integrated STEM for teachers with students in grades 5 8  Instructor   Rachel Martin  Educator and Science Department Head MathScience Innovation Center Rachel Martin is an educator and department chair at the MathScience Innovation Center in Richmond Virginia  Her experiential educational philosophy was created after spending a semester in college studying environmental science in Australia where she swam with sharks on the Great Barrier Reef  ate breakfast with a platypus  and became a host to countless leeches while exploring the rainforests of Australia  Thanks in part to the myriad of phenomenal educators in her life  she pursued her Master of Arts in Education degree from the College of William and Mary to pass on the love of learning  Following her teaching experiences in middle school science  she became a biology  earth science and environmental science educator for the MathScience Innovation Center in 2005  Over the past 10 years  Rachel has been involved with numerous keystone projects including fractal geometry  virtual lessons  nanoscience  environmental sustainability and engineering  Coding Curiosity   Grades 3 8  Administrators The concept of elementary and middle school students coding is absolutely amazing  Coding is a skill that teaches students strategy  problem solving  and breaking down tasks  Teachers are intrigued with coding but are not sure where to start  Through this session we will help you figure out where can you start and where can you go  Participants will learn about apps  websites and toys that will spark the coding curiosity of elementary and middle school students  You will even have a chance to control toys through your own code  We will end the session talking about school wide programs and parent involved activities to expand the coding experience in your school  No experience necessary   Hands On  This workshop covers computer science for teachers and administrators with students in grades 3 8   Instructor   Susan Jinks  Ph  D  Technology Specialist  Mary Ellen Henderson Middle School Dr  Susan Jinks is an instructional technology specialist at Mary Ellen Henderson Middle School  MEH  in Falls Church City  VA  MEh has just completed its first year as a 1 1 laptop school  After successfully co writing a grant  Jinks helped to establish a Makerspace in the school library  She recently became a Google Educator and Google for Education Certified Trainer  Her doctoral work focused on the factors that lead to the perception of learning within a graduate online course        Crack the Code  Learning with Scratch and Arduino   Grades 3 8 THIS IS A HANDS ON WORKSHOP REQUIRING PARTICIPANTS TO BRING THEIR OWN LAPTOP COMPUTERS  If coding is the new literacy  how do we make it relevant within the context of student learning  Join two elementary educators from Albemarle County Public Schools in an experiential investigation of infusing coding and electronics into the curriculum  Participants will explore Arduino micro controllers  http www arduino cc  and Scratch programming  https scratch mit edu  Discover how Scratch is useful for making interactive scenes  video games  and more  while Arduino empowers students to add responsive  electronic elements to any item  Both platforms promote problem solving  critical thinking  and logical reasoning while naturally introducing challenges and community investigation along the way  Come to this hands on session ready to tinker  play  and create your own products  You will learn as a student by writing code  setting up a circuit to make a light blink using Arduino  or animating a figure in Scratch as an introduction  developing your own strategies for problem solving with the challenges presented  Even those with no prior experience will be poised to take these tools into classrooms immediately  Provide your students with yet another set of tools that they can use to solve meaningful problems and make sense of learning in any content area in elementary school and beyond  The possibilities are endless  This workshop covers Technology for teachers with students in grades 3 8  Instructors     Andrea Atkinson  Library Media Specialist  Lewis Elementary Andrea Atkinson  B S M L I S  has over 20 years of pre school through 12th grade teaching experience in a combination of classroom and library settings  After spending 19 years of her career in Michigan  Andrea relocated to Charlottesville to become the Library Media Specialist at Meriwether Lewis Elementary in Albemarle County  She focuses her efforts on creating a centralized learning place for exploration and discovery by students and teachers  A true lifelong learner herself  Andrea appropriately balances print and electronic resources   Stephanie Passman  Gifted Resource Teacher  Stony Point Elementary Stephanie Passmanis the Gifted Resource Teacher at Albemarle s Stony Point Elementary School  and has previously been an upper elementary classroom teacher in Charlottesville and Phoenix  She focuses on collaborating with K 5 teachers to create student centered learning experiences  She also runs the school s Maker Space to promote creation and innovation  Both educators work to inspire students to take control of their learning and move it to the next level  Creating a Culture of STEM in Elementary School   Grades 3 6  Administrators Perry Harrison School will share their story of creating a STEM culture in an elementary school  We will share how building a STEM team and incorporating community goals into a successful STEM program  We will share integrating other academic areas into your STEM program  This workshop covers project based learning for teaches and administrators with students in grades 3 6  Instructors   Freda Hicks  Principal  Perry Harrison Elementary School Freda Hicks is currently the principal of Perry Harrison Elementary School in Pittsboro  NC  Perry Harrison was recently named a top three STEM elementary school by FETC in Orlando Florida  She has lead Perry Harrison s transformation to a STEM focused school the past three years   Kimberly Boyer  Teacher Perry Harrison Elementary School   Elizabeth Sturdivant  Teacher  Perry Harrison Elementary School   Creating an Elementary MakerSpace   grades 3 6 Come hear and see how you can create a MakerSpace in your elementary school  It might have to be a traveling Rubbermaid tub because you are on a bare bones budget and there aren t any extra classrooms in your building or you might have a designated classroom to fill with materials and are generously funded by grant money  We ve done it both ways and will tell you how we did it and what stuff you will need to be ready to engage Kindergartners through 5th graders in making  building  problem solving  and creating through experiences in science  technology  engineering  and math  PowerPoint lecture with questions answers discussion  participants will get handouts listing suggested MakerSpace supplies and sources of these supplies  This workshop covers integrated STEM for teachers with students in grades 3 6  Instructors     Anne Barrow  Elementary Gifted Education Teacher  Bedford County Public Schools Anne Barrow is a former Camp Director turned Gifted Education Teacher who has implemented school wide STEM events and created MakerSpaces at both of her elementary schools   Kelly Steele  Gifted Education Teacher  Bedford County Public School Kelly Steele is a former Chemical Engineer turned Gifted Education Teacher whose MakerSpace experiences and STEM teaching at her schools operate out of traveling Rubbermaid tubs  Critical Creative Thinking and Standards of Learning do Mix  Easy recipes to make it work in your classroom   Grades 3 4  5 6  Administrators Discover how easy it is to integrate STEM and children s engineering into your existing curriculum  In this interactive session  presenters will demonstrate the use of VA DOE Design Briefs and use children s literature to encourage critical thinking and problem solving while targeting specific standards  Participants will have access to a repository of design briefs and hands on activities to enhance their daily instruction  This Workshop Covers   Integrated STEM Instructors   Terri Vangelos  Gifted Resource Teacher  Montgomery County Public Schools An experienced educator with 15  years in the classroom  who has focused on gifted education by providing extension and challenge for K 5 students and support to their regular ed teachers during the past 6 years  Mrs  Vangelos was named Region IV Gifted Teacher of the Year by the Virginia Association for the Gifted in 2015   Becca Rainey  Library Media Specialist  MCPS   Belview Elementary School  Diane Naff  Supervisor of Gifted Programs  Montgomery County Public School Developing STEM Initiatives in the Rural School District   Grades 3 8  Administrators In order to implement an effective STEM program in a rural school district  one must understand the nature and needs of such unique communities  This session will discuss the five components of developing a high school STEM program  The first component will focus on the use of incorporating data so that the division recognizes the need for STEM initiatives  This may even include assisting in dissolving traditional district boundaries  Component two will focus on identifying stakeholders who would develop a steering committee  community partnerships  community  local industry and post secondary education  and an advocate for the process  This component will show that a rural community needs to come together with resources to create a lasting and effective STEM education infrastructure  This leads into the third component  Professional development and fourth component  Technology  It is extremely important that educators within the division adopt and are trained in the effective use of technology and distance learning  The final component is the capstone of the program which includes internships and the inclusion of CTE programs  This workshop covers integrated STEM for teachers and administrators with students in grades 3 8  Instructors     Thomas Johnson III High School Assistant Principal STEM Program Chair Accomack County Public Schools Mr  Thomas Johnson III is currently serving as the Assistant Principal for Nandua Middle School in Accomack County  He is the leading advocate and chairperson of the Accomack County Public Schools STEM Academy which is starting the third successful year in operation  Mr  Johnson has earned a Bachelor of Science in Mathematics from Longwood College  a Masters in Education from North Georgia State University and Educational Specialist degree in Educational Leadership from Jones University   Rebecca Johnson  Facilitator of Gifted Resources Accomack County Public Schools Design on a Plate   Grades 3 4  5 6 This hands on workshop is designed for teachers in grades 3 6  This specific activity is designed to augment VA Math SOL 3 10  5 8 and 5 9 in a way that allows both special education and gifted students to participate in the same classroom activity  The attendees will take on the role of student to design a landscape or building plate using graphing paper  They will then transfer their design to a lego building plate using Lego bricks  supplied by presenters  The attendees will then calculate the area and perimeter with volume and circumference added for the gifted cluster  At the end of the session attendees will have the opportunity to brainstorm and share other activities that could be designed with LEGO building blocks  This workshop covers mathematics for grades 3 6  Instructors   Nancy Northcott  Seaford Elementary School  York County School Division Mrs  Northcott is a fifth grade teacher at Seaford Elementary School  She is a gifted and inclusion teacher for York County  Mathematics is her specialty area  She is also the co sponsor of Seaford Elementary s Robotics Team  She is trained in Transformative Project based Learning and have implemented various projects in their classrooms that encompass more than one content area   Connie Hayes  4th Grade Teacher  Seaford Elementary School  York County School Division Mrs  Hayes is a fourth grade teacher at Seaford Elementary School  She is the fourth grade inclusion teacher  as well as a trained autism specialist  She is a math teacher and the co sponsor of Seaford s Robotics Team  She is trained in Transformative Project based Learning and have implemented various projects in their classrooms that encompass more than one content area  Edmodo in the classroom   Grades K 8 During the workshop  attendees  who have internet access and device  will see how this FREE web based platform  Edmodo can be integrated in the classroom  Attendees will be able to see how students are able to communicate with the teacher and their peers  access additional resources  take quizzes tests and turn in assignments without a single piece of paper  No more taking papers home and loosing them  Attendees will see how this can be used for a variety of ages and subjects  see professional resources available through Edmodo and collaborate with students and colleagues  Attendees will take away how to set up Edmodo at their school  set up classes  join professional communities and work on their own classroom  library  Edmodo will meet digital literacy and many technology standards  Attendees would benefit more with internet access and a device  and this will be a VERY hands on workshop  This workshop covers Project Based Learning for teachers grades 3 8 and administrators  Instructor   Kristi Meyers  teacher  St  Leo the Great Catholic School Kristi Meyers is a science nerd and student professed tree hugger  14 years of combined public and private school teaching experience  BS in Elementary education and MS in curriculum instruction and design  Always looking to integrate technology into the classroom to meet student individual needs and reaching students using 21st century communication skills  Engineering Design Challenges  Capitalizing on the Expertise of Local Industry   Grades 3 8  Administrators How do I prepare my students to be college  career and citizen ready  Bring your students together to collaborate in rigorous  career based engineering design challenges  EDC  An EDC breaks down the barriers between the STEM disciplines and exposes students to STEM careers  capitalizing on the expertise of local industry  By partnering with local industry  educators can develop learning experiences that are relevant and require students to apply their knowledge to solve real world problems  Through these challenges students acquire STEM skills that will prepare them for high demand  high wage  and high skill careers in Virginia  In this hands on workshop  you will experience two exemplar engineering design challenges by assuming a career and devising a quantifiable solution to a real world problem  Participants will have an opportunity to develop an individualized action plan and  if desired  continue to network through an online community  This workshop covers integrated STEM for grades 3 8  Instructors   Jacob Andrus  STEM Instructional Specialist  Newport News Public Schools Jacob Andrus has been actively involved in STEM education for several years and is extremely passionate about ensuring all students participate in engaging and rigorous STEM educational experiences  Jacob is a STEM Instructional Specialist for Newport News Public Schools and has created a pipeline of STEM programming for elementary and middle school students  He has experience in various areas of public education including school leadership  curriculum development  and elementary education  In addition to his work in Newport News Public Schools  Jacob is an adjunct professor at Christopher Newport University in the College of Natural and Behavioral Sciences  Jacob received his Masters in Educational Leadership from Regent University and his Bachelors of Science from Radford University     Tami Byron  STEM Instructional Specialist  Newport News Public Schools Tami Byron is a STEM Instructional Specialist for Newport News Public Schools  She has 15 years of experience in various areas of education including special education  elementary education  and middle secondary education  Tami s current projects include the design and development of elementary integrative STEM curriculum and elementary middle school division wide design challenges for Newport News Public Schools  Tami was awarded a Programs that Work award by the Virginia Math and Science Coalition in 2015  for the design and implementation of the iSTEM Innovation Institute teacher professional development program  She desires to expand STEM literacy into the classroom by empowering teachers with the expertise to develop and implement standards aligned  problem based  inquiry learning experiences that solve real world problems with career connections  Tami earned a Bachelor s of Science degree from Liberty University and is currently enrolled in McDaniel College s graduate STEM certificate program  Engineering with Cardboard   Grades 3 8 We plan to share strategies  some useful tools  and planning ideas to creating cardboard engineering challenges  We will talk about the Rube Goldberg machines that 4th graders created this spring  as well as some other cardboard engineering projects that 3rd and 2nd graders worked on  This will be a hands on workshop in which attendees will participate in an engineering challenge that we create for them  Our goal is to have attendees leave ready to try a cardboard engineering challenge with their students  These challenges cover the Force and Motion strand of the science SOLs  as well as Measurement  Data  and Graphing in Math SOLs  Planning and Reflective writing SOLs are also incorporated  This workshop covers project based learning for grades 3 8  Instructors    Helen Miller  Classroom Teacher  ACPS  Helen Miller is a 3rd grade teacher  Brooke Asher is a 4th grade teacher  and Peggy Riso is a 2nd grade teacher at Cale Elementary School in Albemarle County  Virginia  We have collaborated on cross curricular science  technology  and math  We are leading our school as we pilot an Imagination Foundation chapter www imagination is    Brooke Asher  Classroom Teacher  ACPS Girl s Geek Day  What s THAT    Grades 3 8  Administrators This workshop will cover the basics of starting up a Girl s Geek Day  which can be adapted to just about any audience  We will also share our experiences and ideas for sessions and the organization we use to work with students new to us each time we hold one  Participants will problem solve as they utilize some of our technology tools  brainstorm and use engineering design principles as they work with some of our STEM equipment  and share and collaborate as we work together to craft an entertaining  yet informative 50 minutes  This workshop covers integrated STEM for teachers and administrators of students in grades 3 8  Instructors     Paula White  Gifted Resources Teacher  Albemarle County Public Schools Paula is a learner 