different engineering programs for teachers  such as the VA STEM CoNNECT  as well as developing STEM Career programs for school counselors  Throughout her professional career  Kristine has been involved in developing and presenting professional developments on a local to national level  Her last two presentations were featured at the Regional NCTM Conference and the NSTA STEM Forum  Astronomical Tools   How to Use Them   Grades 3 8 Today there are a number of astronomical tools  telescopes  cameras  software  websites  available that an educator can use to enhance their student s learning experience  It can be a daunting task wading through all the options  and choosing the right one is not always easy  Once you have made your choice learning to use the tool can also be a time consuming task  where do you turn to for help  In this workshop we will give you an introduction to what s available in the way of tools and resources that are suitable for various education levels  From free to pricey we give you a rundown on what s out there  the  good  the bad  and the ugly  and where to get help  We will present the basics of how to choose and use binoculars  telescopes  cameras  and software as well as what to look for  and look out for  when it s time for you to make your choice  Weather permitting there will be an optional observing session in the evening   See the schedule for details  This workshop covers technology for educators and administrators with students in grades 3 8  Instructors     Lt  Col  Gregory Topasna  Ph  D  Department of Physics   Astronomy  Virginia Military Institute Dr  Topasna is a Professor of Physics at Virginia Military Institute in Lexington  VA  He is a graduate from VA Tech with a Ph D  in Physics and a concentration in astronomy  He has been teaching physics and astronomy since joining the VMI faculty in 2000 and conducts astronomical research on the polarization of starlight and the interstellar medium  Additionally  Dr  Topasna works with Dr  Daniela Topasna in the thin films laboratory at VMI where they fabricate and characterize thin film devices as well as Janus particles    Lt  Col  Daniela Topasna  Ph  D  Department of Physics   Astronomy  Virginia Military Institute Dr  Topasna is an associate professor in the department of physics and astronomy at Virginia Military Institute  Her research interests include fabrication and characterization of self assembled thin films  She has presented and authored several outreach activities in physics and nanotechnology Astronomical Tools   How to Use Them   Grades 3 8 Today there are a number of astronomical tools  telescopes  cameras  software  websites  available that an educator can use to enhance their student s learning experience  It can be a daunting task wading through all the options  and choosing the right one is not always easy  Once you have made your choice learning to use the tool can also be a time consuming task  where do you turn to for help  In this workshop we will give you an introduction to what s available in the way of tools and resources that are suitable for various education levels  From free to pricey we give you a rundown on what s out there  the  good  the bad  and the ugly  and where to get help  We will present the basics of how to choose and use binoculars  telescopes  cameras  and software as well as what to look for  and look out for  when it s time for you to make your choice  Weather permitting there will be an optional observing session in the evening   See the schedule for details  This workshop covers technology for educators and administrators with students in grades 3 8  Instructors     Lt  Col  Gregory Topasna  Ph  D  Department of Physics   Astronomy  Virginia Military Institute Dr  Topasna is a Professor of Physics at Virginia Military Institute in Lexington  VA  He is a graduate from VA Tech with a Ph D  in Physics and a concentration in astronomy  He has been teaching physics and astronomy since joining the VM