ame a Certified Financial Counselor through the Credit Union National Association s FiCep program  She is a 2012 graduate of the Harrisonburg Rockingham Leadership program and a two time winner of the Desjardin Youth Financial Education Award for the state of Virginia  Sarah is also a certified trainer for the National Endowment for Financial Education  Prior to joining the Financial Education department  Sarah worked for 17 years in the Retail area at DCCU CAREERS Project based Learning Program The Creative and Real World Engaging Experiences Realized this Summer  CAREERS  program was created for at risk and low performing 7th and 8th grade students as an alternative to a traditional summer school  Furthermore  research has shown that college and career readiness should be started in the middle school to help assess personal interest and future goals through career exploration  The program hired teachers to create project based learning units that were created around the 16 career clusters  Each project focused on competencies of problem solving  flexibility  collaboration and time management  It also embedded reading and math skills  The culminating project was for students to select one project and create a visual representation of the process of how they worked to create a project to answer a driving question or solve a challenge  In addition  students researched a potential career cluster of interest and presented it to community members  The hands on presentation will showcase the many projects that included some STEM PBL  MakerSpace  water rocket science  textile engineering  technologically related projects  t shirt shop  and the culminating project  Participants will examine the projects at different stations and fill out a handout that will prompt them to ask questions  write observations and how it could be used in other schools  After the activity  the presenters will answer questions  discuss the benefits and lessons learned from the program  The attendees will receive ideas and ways to incorporate project based learning units that include STEM and technology into their curriculum  The SOLSs covered will be non fiction reading skills  physical science SOLs and various math standards  This workshop covers project based learning for teachers and administrators with students in grades 7 8  Instructors      Rory Dippold  Ph  D CAREERS Coordinator   Civics   Economics Teacher  Falls Church City Schools Dr  Dippold is a Nationally Board Certified Teacher who has taught for twelve years in Falls Church City Schools  He is a Civics   Economics teacher who incorporates project based learning into his curriculum to create authentic learning experiences  In addition  his dissertation was titled   Infusing Self regulation Learning into Project based Learning  and he currently serves as an adjunct professor at George Mason University  He was recently honored as a Virginia Lottery  Super Teacher  award winner   Susan Jinks  Ph  D Technology Instructional Coach  Falls Church City Schools CAREERS Project based Learning Program The Creative and Real World Engaging Experiences Realized this Summer  CAREERS  program was created for at risk and low performing 7th and 8th grade students as an alternative to a traditional summer school  Furthermore  research has shown that college and career readiness should be started in the middle school to help assess personal interest and future goals through career exploration  The program hired teachers to create project based learning units that were created around the 16 career clusters  Each project focused on competencies of problem solving  flexibility  collaboration and time management  It also embedded reading and math skills  The culminating project was for students to select one project and create a visual representation of the process of how they worked to create a project to answer a driving question or solve a challenge  In addition  students researched a potential career cluster of i