o the classroom  Lastly we will discuss other opportunities for students to apply energy concepts through engineering design challenges  This workshop covers technology for teachers and administrators with students in grades 3 8 Instructor   Cindy Kleveckis  Center for Wind Energy  James Madison University Power your Classroom with Renewable Energy   Grades 3 8  Administrators During this workshop participants will learn about the potential and logistics of installing a wind turbine and or solar panels at their school  We will discuss the new Virginia Wind for Schools Program and work with hands on wind and solar energy curricula that can be used to integrate the renewable energy technology into the classroom  Lastly we will discuss other opportunities for students to apply energy concepts through engineering design challenges  This workshop covers technology for teachers and administrators with students in grades 3 8 Instructor   Cindy Kleveckis  Center for Wind Energy  James Madison University This workshop covers technology for teachers and administrators with students in grades 3 8 Putting the  T  in STEM Learning   Grades 3 8 Are you overwhelmed with the idea of integrating STEM tools in the classroom  Do you need help determining what tool would be the best fit for you and your students  Is cost the factor  Grade appropriateness  Subject area  Or maybe you need ideas on how integrate tools into your curriculum needs  Come learn and experience 5 STEM learning tools and how they can facilitate interdisciplinary classroom experiences including a hands on showcase of Squishy Circuits  Makey Makey  Finch Robot  Hummingbird Robotics  and LilyPad Arduino  The presenters will share these tools and the research gained from using them in the classroom  as well as share some of the challenges and successes with implementations  Attendees will get the opportunity to see example projects  learn about ways they have been integrated into multiple subject areas and SOLs  and ignite an interest in utilizing these tools into their own classrooms  In addition to the showcasing of 5 STEM learning tools  the presenters will share additional STEM tools that could be used in the classroom  Although part of the workshop will be lecture  there will be time to explore the tools and projects  ask questions  and brainstorm with the other attendees  This workshop covers technology for teachers with students in grades 3 8  Instructors   Paula Leach  Ph D  Director  Longwood University   Institute for Teaching through Technology and Innovative Practices Dr  Paula Klonowski Leach is the director of Longwood University s Institute for Teaching through Technology and Innovative Practices  ITTIP  Dr  Leach previously was a STEM learning specialist at ITTIP  an educational outreach of Longwood that helps teachers incorporate technology into the classroom and disseminates research based best practices in schools  She provides professional development to K 12 teachers  focusing on using emerging technologies in mathematics and science  Dr  Leach was also the state science coordinator for the Virginia Department of Education for eight years  She has also filled the role of division science coordinator  as well as a middle school science and special education teacher  for the Powhatan County schools  A native of Lower Burrell  Pa  near Pittsburgh  Leach is a graduate of Slippery Rock University and has her master s and doctoral degrees from Virginia Commonwealth University   Stephanie Playton  STEM Learning Specialist  Longwood University   Institute for Teaching through Technology and Innovative Practices Putting the  T  in STEM Learning   Grades 3 8 Are you overwhelmed with the idea of integrating STEM tools in the classroom  Do you need help determining what tool would be the best fit for you and your students  Is cost the factor  Grade appropriateness  Subject area  Or maybe you need ideas on how integrate tools into your curriculum needs  Come learn and e